Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany
Report on the audit
Foreword
Taxes are the main source of revenue for public budgets.
A focus of the work of the courts of auditors should therefore be on the examination of this area.
This applies in particular to VAT fraud.
This alone results in an estimated €100 billion in annual tax losses in the European Union.
At the sixth EUROSAI Congress in Bonn in 2005, the participants pointed out the need for enhanced cooperation.
This allows the courts of auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and to optimise audit practice.
VAT is particularly suitable for cooperation, as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, the courts of auditors of both States audited for the first time in parallel in the field of UST.
The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.
Since UST fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the courts of auditors is needed, which will allow for a comprehensive assessment of whether the measures taken are suitable for dealing effectively with UST fraud.
The two courts of auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany report on the audit
1. Introduction
Exam Number: (CZ) 09 / 11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Subject of audit: (CZ) administration of the UST (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter nkú), audit
The aim of the examination is to:
(CZ) the UST administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as Germany) should be examined, as well as the procedures used by the financial authorities for intergovernmental assistance.
(D) The audit should evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the audit bodies.
In addition, further examination fields linked to the Ust should be processed.
The findings made here should be compared to determine whether tax procedures can be optimised.
The examination period was from 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period before the examination period until the completion of the examination.
2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The courts of auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed to an audit of the administration of the UST.
In the previous parallel examination, they revealed suspicions of intra-Community turnover,
Which made a further examination seem expedient.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two courts of auditors issued recommendations for the administration of UST.
The aim of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented and to examine the suspected cases identified.
The audit also looked at other issues, including selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of UST claims and the UST audit of large companies.
The courts of auditors have stated that:
1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous examination
• recommendation 1: the rules for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU
During the initial audit, the courts of auditors compared UST registration procedures in the two states and noted differences that caused problems.
The courts of auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.
This has also been taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798 / 2003 provides for the extension of current databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of UST users.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their possible deletion.
The courts of auditors expected Member States to agree on appropriate rules in accordance with their decision of principle to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the Ust system as early as possible.
Member States reached political agreement on the final version of the draft in Ecofin.
The above-mentioned common rules are no longer included, and the two courts of auditors regret that.
They still consider such regulations to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.
• recommendation 2: monthly submission of the summary reports as a result of the first audit, the courts of auditors recommended to the Member States that the summary reports (ZM) should be submitted monthly in the future.
The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be reviewed in a timely manner.
Council Directive 2008 / 117 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the common system of Value Added Tax (VAT) for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has reduced the deadline for the payment of the ZM to one month.
In the Czech Republic, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the Ust Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.
In Germany, the implementation did not enter into force until 1 July 2010, which means that it did not implement the obligation to pay the ZM monthly into national law on time.
• recommendation 3: data comparison of UST pre-filings and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAs data and proposal to examine the merging of procedures for Ust pre-filings and Zm. The German Financial Administration has taken up the recommendation issued by the Federal Court of Auditors and set up a working group to work out possible solutions.
The work has not yet been completed.
The Federal Court of Auditors will monitor further developments.
• recommendation 4: exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level during the initial audit, the two audit bodies agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The courts of auditors noted that the two Member States apply different risk management systems, which have both strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - Eurocanet, while the Federal Court of Auditors focused on German participation in the "Platform for risk management."
2. Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
During the first audit, the courts of auditors jointly examined transactions where it was doubtful whether they had actually been executed or which had been explained differently by the taxpayers of the two states in the Ust preliminary filings (or UST declarations) or ZM.
For the audit, the courts of auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany.
The audits by the tax authorities (FÄ) of both states had not yet been completed when the first parallel audit was completed.
The audit found that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed, with appropriate measures taken by the respective tax authorities (including ex-post tax provisions or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community transactions
The audit also included high-risk intra-Community transactions between taxpayers in the EU covered by the Eurocanet system.
Eurocanet is used to identify high-risk taxpayers.
Member States can participate in this system on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active participant in Eurocanet. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of Eurocanet.
From the point of view of an active participant state, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
As a result, no information could be obtained as to which suppliers with German USt Id would have been classified as high-risk cases.
The NKU found both normal business transactions and those with suspected UST fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected transactions.
The FÄ were only able to examine transactions with high risk to a limited extent, especially in the case of so-called "missing traders," whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove the taxable fraud.
Suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports
It is recommended that customs and tax authorities work more closely together to monitor the proximity of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the end user.
Germany, as well as a number of other countries, have rejected active participation in Eurocanet because they do not believe there is a sufficient legal basis.
The Federal Court of Auditors found that the German Financial Administration uses other instruments to identify risk-bearing taxpayers.
However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation,
Created by the Eurofisc.
The experience gained so far with Eurocanet should be incorporated into the planned network to combat UST fraud.
4. Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
Therefore, requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic and Germany will be dealt with in the same way.
The Federal Court of Auditors and NKU compared the statistics that both Member States submitted to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two courts of auditors consider it useful to re-discuss the statistics at EU level in order to avoid future discrepancies.
If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should include more information on UST.
Analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat UST fraud.
Both courts believe that Member States with a low rate of recovery should strive to achieve at least the average rate of recovery.
The Commission should support the Member States in this, if they so wish.
5. Ust test at large companies
The courts of auditors analysed the legal situation regarding the UST audit of large companies in both states.
In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from the tax authorities, which they considered important in this context.
It was clear that the situation is different in both states.
The CZ has a system for selecting high-risk cases that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on UST audits, balance sheet data, profit and loss statements).
Overall, UST control can thus be effectively controlled and analysed.
A special tax office for large companies is to be set up in 2012.
In Germany, there is no comparable system yet. This makes the control and analysis of UST control more difficult overall.
The German financial administration is focusing more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the Ust preliminary filings or UST declarations and the Zm.
Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.
