4. Audit of the management of VAT in selected areas
4.1 implementation of the recommendations of the first joint audit
4.1.1 implementation of the recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for registration of taxable persons within the EU
Following the results of the first audit, the Czech court of auditors recommended that the requirements for VAT registration be adjusted and that new rules be introduced for the cancellation of registration in the Czech Republic.
These amended Rules should more effectively reduce the risk of possible tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that the FÄ did not erase the VAT registration of taxpayers if they did not comply with their obligations under Czech law No. 235 / 2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "Ust Act").
So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted an amendment to require the FÄ to be cancelled if taxpayers repeatedly fail to submit UST declarations.
Under the Czech UST Act, the FA may cancel the registration of a taxable person ex officio if (a) the taxable person has not made transactions for twelve consecutive months and has not informed the Fa of the reasons for doing so; (b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations under the UST act; (c) the taxable person no longer meets the requirements for the tax obligation.
The first examination showed that, due to the existing legal situation, the Prague 1 company must delete the UST registration of "foreign taxpayers" 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year, if they were not obliged to register and pay UST in the current calendar year.
The Prague 1 company often did not erase the VAT registration of these taxpayers because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the amendment of the UST law, which entered into force on 1 January 2009.
According to this, the FA is entitled to cancel the registration of a foreign taxable person if he has not provided taxable or tax-exempt goods or services with the right to deduct VAT in the previous calendar year.
Recommendation 2
Monthly Levy of the ZM
On the basis of the initial audit, the courts of auditors had recommended that the monthly levy of Zm be introduced.
The Council Directive, which reduced the frequency of the ZM levy to one month, was implemented in the Czech Republic by the UST Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
The ZM must now be delivered electronically.
In addition, a Zm must be issued if services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with § 9 (1) Ust law are provided to a person registered as a VAT payer in another Member State.
The condition is that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the VAT for these services, as required by Council Directive 2008 / 8 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC as regards the location of the service.
Recommendation 3
Comparison of the data of the UST preliminary filings and the ZM to increase the reliability of the MIAS data this recommendation referred to the German financial administration.
The Czech Financial Administration automatically compares the data on intra-Community transactions from the Ust declarations and the ZM in its system, ATI 4.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of VAT is a sine qua non for the proper functioning of the EU's internal market.
That is why the fight against UST fraud is of primary interest and has received significant attention in recent years.
The importance of this is demonstrated, among other things, by an investigation published by the European Commission in October 2009.
In it, an external expert estimated the loss of VAT for the 25 Member States in the period 2000 to 2006. Based on the available data, the tax loss for the said period was estimated to be between 90 and 113 billion euros, based on the fact that the EU-25 loses an average of 12% of their sales taxes each year.
The estimated tax loss for CZ in 2006 was 18%.
The first audit found that a Member State alone cannot develop an effective risk management system (RMS).
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
In relation to the RMS, the Czech court of Auditors has examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (Eurocanet).
For this purpose, risk-bearing intra-Community transactions carried out by taxpayers within the EU and recorded in Eurocanet were selected (see chapter 4.3).
The Eurofisc network is designed to optimise administrative assistance in tax matters and to combat VAT fraud more effectively, and to improve cooperation between the competent authorities in order to identify cases of fraud as early as possible.
Eurofisc could later be used as a tool to estimate the risk potential of intra-Community sales.
ECOFIN Council 6 already approved Eurofisc on 7 October 2008 and at the same time adopted the principles governing the functioning of the system.
Eurofisc is modelled on Eurocanet, which was developed by the Belgian financial administration in cooperation with the other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and olaf7.
The purpose of the system is to detect risky transactions and identify entrepreneurs involved in the organised VAT fraud.
