4.2 review of selected intra-Community transactions
During the initial audit, a joint investigation was carried out into transactions where there were doubts as to whether they had actually been carried out or whether discrepancies had been found in the declarations of taxpayers in both Member States.
The two courts of auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany for the audit, where the tax audit by the authorities of the Member State concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint audit.
1)
In the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer purchased goods worth 22 686 euros from a German taxpayer.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the acquisition in his VAT statement, since the period specified in the German tax ordinance did not have a VAT identification number, but only a tax number for intra-German transactions.
Through international assistance in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the competent Czech company obtained information that according to the German UST Act, the supplier of intra-Community goods does not need an UST identification number in order to be able to claim the tax exemption for intra-Community goods deliveries.
The audit carried out by the Czech court of Auditors found that, according to the audit of the competent Czech company, the Czech taxpayer submitted an additional VAT declaration declaring the purchase of goods of the above value and at the same time claiming his right to deduct the same amount of VAT.
2)
In the fourth quarter of 2004, a Czech taxpayer was said to have purchased goods worth 12,561 euros from a German taxpayer.
However, he said he did not acquire the goods and therefore did not explain them in his UST statement.
The German financial administration, citing a provision of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, declined to process the request because the turnover linked to the acquisition did not exceed the threshold of 15 000 euros.
Since the Czech FA was unable to obtain any documents, the tax audit was inconclusive and the original tax determination remained in place.
The audit by the Czech court of Auditors found that the Czech FA from Germany received two spontaneous information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, according to which the German taxpayer had charged a Slovak addressee for the delivery of the goods in question.
The Czech taxpayer acquired the goods from the Slovak taxpayer and stated the purchase in its regular VAT declaration for the month of October 2004.
3)
In the fourth quarter of 2004, a Czech taxpayer was said to have bought a car worth 48 500 euros from a German taxpayer.
However, he did not declare an intra-Community acquisition.
In addition, he had not issued an UST statement since August 2004, which is why the UST was set at CZK 0 for the quarter in question.
On the basis of information received from Germany in the course of the international exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the FA asked the taxpayer in March 2007 to submit a subsequent tax return, but the taxpayer did not do so.
The audit found that in 2007, the company had carried out further investigations in this tax case, finding that the car in question had been sold by the taxpayer to a second-hand car dealer in the Czech Republic.
The Czech FA carried out a tax assessment for the tax period of December 2004, setting additional taxes of 295 379 CZK for the purchase and resale of goods from another Member State.
The competent Czech court decided to open insolvency proceedings on the assets of the Czech taxpayer; an insolvency administrator has been appointed.
In the absence of significant assets, the outstanding tax liability is likely to be irrecoverable.
4)
In the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer is said to have delivered new vehicles (passenger cars) with a total value of 198 167 euros to Germany.
In response to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, it was stated that tax proceedings were pending against the German taxpayer in Germany.
The audit by the Federal Court of Auditors found that after the conclusion of the proceedings there was evidence of the involvement of the German taxpayer in fraud.
The intra-Community acquisition of goods was subject to employment taxation in the amount of 182 424 Euros (for 2004) and 369 690 euros (for 2005).
The audit carried out by the Czech court of Auditors found that the Czech taxpayer was involved in carousel fraud involving new vehicles.
On the basis of information provided by the German tax administration, a VAT audit of the Czech taxpayer took place for the tax periods April, May and June 2005.
Based on the findings of the audit and the information from the international exchange of information, the FA determined additional VAT of CZK 703 031 for May 2005 and CZK 726 551 for June 2005.
5)
In February 2005, the Czech taxpayer a was said to have acquired a machine with a total value of 58 000 euros from a German taxpayer.
In the third quarter of 2004, the German taxpayer was said to have delivered a machine to the Czech taxpayer B worth 88 027 euros. However, B denied the acquisition.
The audit carried out by the Czech court of Auditors found that B had acquired the machine from a German company with a branch in the Czech Republic.
The Czech taxpayer a did not specify the purchase of the goods by the German taxpayer named in his VAT statement.
The German company's response to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 found that the German taxpayer had not made an intra-Community delivery of a machine worth 58 000 euros, but a delivery within the Czech Republic.
In the audit, the Federal Court of Auditors found that the intra-Community delivery of the machine was classified as domestic delivery after the completion of an audit and that the exemption from VAT was subsequently refused.
6)
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxpayer is said to have delivered goods worth €11,600 to a Czech taxpayer.
The goods were purchased and later sold in Germany in 2005.
The audit carried out by the Czech court of Auditors found that the Czech FA had made its assessment on the basis of a supplementary statement issued by the UST, which inadmissibly identified purchases from another Member State, including purchases in the above amount.
The Federal Court of Auditors found that after receiving a reply to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the German FA rectified the VAT declaration of the German taxpayer and set an additional VAT of 1,600 euros.
Due to the resale of the goods in Germany and the corresponding UST assessment there, an examination is ongoing.
The ZM of the German taxpayer has not yet been corrected, since in Germany only the taxpayer who has surrendered the ZM can correct it.
7)
The competent Czech company received a request for information from the German tax administration in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 on the question of the purchase of a car worth 47 400 euros by a Czech taxpayer in February 2005.
After an audit for the 2005 tax period, the Czech FA determined the tax liability of the Czech taxpayer at CZK 0 and informed the German FA that it could not confirm the purchase of the car by the Czech taxpayer.
The audit carried out by the Czech court of Auditors found that the registration of the Czech VAT payer had been cancelled because it had not complied with its tax obligations.
The Czech FA had sent the documents to the Czech police.
The German taxpayer has not yet corrected his information in the ZM, but has appealed against the tax ruling.
8)
According to mias10, between the third quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a German taxpayer supplied a Czech taxpayer with a total value of 33 205 euros, which he did not declare to be an intra-Community acquisition.
The audit of the Czech court of Auditors found that the Czech FA investigated the reasons for the discrepancies.
The Czech taxpayer issued repeated subsequent VAT declarations for the first quarter of 2005.
However, the Czech FA was not able to clarify the difference in the amount of CZK 134 273 in the period from the third quarter of 2004 to the first quarter of 2005, on the grounds that revenues for individual quarters could not be accurately allocated, and accepted the UST statements made.
9)
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxpayer delivered goods worth 46 854 euros to a Czech taxpayer.
For the same period, the Czech taxpayer declared the intra-Community purchase of goods worth only 14 856 euros.
As part of the intergovernmental exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the Czech FA reviewed the actual value of the delivery.
The German reply to this request sent three invoices showing a total value of the delivered goods of 31,998 Euros, i.e. an amount corresponding to the difference between the purchase declared by the Czech taxpayer and the MIAS data.
According to the result of the audit by the Czech court of Auditors, the Czech taxpayer submitted a subsequent VAT declaration for the tax period July 2004 after repeated reminders from the FA in January 2007.
With this declaration, the taxpayer simultaneously asserted his right to deduct VAT, and his tax liability for the tax period in question remained unchanged.
The audit confirmed that most of the tax procedures relating to the turnover selected for the audit had been completed and that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic and Germany had taken appropriate measures (including subsequent UST provisions or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
4.3 Examination of selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions
4.3.1 findings in the Czech Republic
Eurocanet can be a significant source of information to identify risk-bearing taxpayers in the Member State of acquisition.
In the Czech Republic, the early warning information obtained from Eurocanet will be reviewed by the relevant company in the case of the purchasers.
Since the first quarter of 2008, CZ has included information on turnover and taxable suppliers, which are considered to be at risk, in the Eurocanet system.
Nine Czech taxpayers were selected for the audit,
Entered into the Eurocanet by the financial authorities of other Member States either as suppliers or purchasers.
