Since the German Financial Administration did not participate in the exchange of data via Eurocanet, it was not possible to determine whether suppliers with a German VAT identification number were classified as risk-prone by the German financial administration.
The audit found both normal business transactions and those suspected of carousel fraud or other UST fraud.
In the cases concerned, the FÄ exchanged information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003,
For example:
• The FÄ did not establish any suspicion of risky transactions when examining the early warning information.
The taxpayers in question were constantly monitored because their data was stored in Eurocanet.
• The FÄ did not manage to prove violations of the rules on the calculation of the tax base and VAT on the basis of the accounting documents provided, even though they found discrepancies in the transport and storage of the goods or revealed business relationships with letterbox companies from other Member States.
• The review of individual transactions was complicated because certain taxpayers did not cooperate with the FÄ and could not be contacted.
The competent authorities reviewed most of the high-risk taxpayers and transactions mentioned in Eurocanet's Early Warning Reports.
However, their ability to review risky transactions, especially so-called "missing traders," is limited.
In particular, a mere examination of the documents can hardly provide evidence of fraudulent activity by the taxpayer.
Stricter requirements for the registration of taxpayers for Ust purposes and greater flexibility in the cancellation of registration would help to combat UST fraud.
Taxable persons involved in fraudulent carousel transactions can be registered for VAT purposes, in order to simulate fictitious deliveries of goods across the EU or to issue formally correct tax receipts to other taxable persons, with which they then assert unjustified claims for deduction of VAT.
