4.4 mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
4.4.1 intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic
The legislation on Intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims in the EU is essentially based on:
Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, as well as levies and duties;
Council Directive 2001 / 44 / EC amending Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, as well as levies and duties and VAT and certain excise duties; and
Commission Directive 2002 / 94 / EC laying down detailed implementing rules for certain articles of Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to certain levies, duties, taxes and other measures.
The Czech Republic implemented Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC by Law no. 252 / 2000 on inter-governmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims.
After the adoption of Council Directive 2001 / 44 / EC, it had to be transposed into Czech law. At the same time, the aforementioned law had to be amended.
In this context, the amendment to the Law No. 191 / 2004 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims was adopted.
A new significant piece of legislation was adopted by Commission Regulation (EC) No 1179 / 2008 of 28 November 2008.
The annexes to this Regulation contain new application forms to be used from 1 January 2009. Furthermore, the Regulation makes electronic transmission mandatory and requires the requesting authority to certify the conformity of all documents sent with the respective original.
The main principles of international assistance for the recovery of claims are:
1. The principle of reciprocity applies;
2. Assistance must always be provided only on request and subject to fulfilment of all conditions;
3. Mutual assistance does not extend to claims that are considered to be criminal sanctions in the requested State;
4. The procedure of intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of claims must be carried out in accordance with the national law of the requested State;
5. In the recovery process, foreign claims do not take precedence over domestic claims;
6. The assistance is provided only for the recovery of undisputed claims;
7. The principle of exploitation applies: the requesting state must use all the means it is entitled to under national law to recover the claim.
Law no. 191 / 2004 provides for three forms of mutual assistance: the provision of information, the notification of legal acts and the actual recovery.
Procedures for outgoing requests to other EU Member States
The competent company has to send the request for information, the request for notification of legal acts or the request for recovery together with the documents concerned electronically to the Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic via the relevant Financial Directorate.
The Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic arranges the translation of the request into the language in question, scans it with all the equipment and sends it via the communication network or the CCN / CSI joint interface to the competent financial authority of the State concerned.
A request for recovery aid must meet the following requirements: the claim must exceed EUR 1 500 and must not be older than five years.
The requested authority may refuse collection if the requirements are not met.
